{"title_page": "Miguel Herr\u00e1n", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Miguel Herr\u00e1n\n| image              = Miguel Herr\u00e1n.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Migu\u00e9l Herr\u00e0n\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1996|04|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[M\u00e1laga]], [[Andalusia]], Spain\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Spanish\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2015\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Miguel Herr\u00e1n''' (born 25 April 1996) is a Spanish actor. He is best known for playing the roles of An\u00edbal \"R\u00edo\" Cort\u00e9s in ''[[Money Heist]]'' and Christian Varela Exp\u00f3sito in ''[[\u00c9lite (TV series)|\u00c9lite]]''. In 2016, he won the [[Goya Award for Best New Actor]] for his role in the film ''[[Nothing in Return]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHerr\u00e1n was born in [[M\u00e1laga]] and moved to [[Madrid]] with his mother as a child, where they lived in the [[Chamber\u00ed]] neighborhood. He was not very fond of school and dreamed of growing up to be a car mechanic.\n\n== Career ==\nA chance encounter with actor and director Daniel Guzman in the streets of Malaga led to Herr\u00e1n auditioning for the role of Dario in the film ''[[A cambio de nada]]'', which he won a Goya award for in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/sociedad/celebrities/articulos/miguel-herran-jaime-lorente-rio-denver-casa-de-papel-serie-netflix-asi-son-actores-motos-futbol-atletico-madrid-murcia-malaga-instagram-fans/32356 |title=As\u00ed son Miguel Herr\u00e1n y Jaime Lorente, 'hermanos' dentro y fuera de la pantalla |first=Nuria |last=Hern\u00e1ndez |date=17 July 2018 |access-date=22 July 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329210324/https://www.revistavanityfair.es/sociedad/celebrities/articulos/miguel-herran-jaime-lorente-rio-denver-casa-de-papel-serie-netflix-asi-son-actores-motos-futbol-atletico-madrid-murcia-malaga-instagram-fans/32356 |archive-date=29 March 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he was cast as Rio in the Antena 3 series ''[[La casa de papel]]'', which was later picked up by Netflix. In 2018, he starred as Christian Varela Exp\u00f3sito in the [[Netflix]] original series ''[[Elite]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/elite-netflix-cast |title=Meet the Cast of \"Elite,\" Netflix's Thrilling New Mystery Series |first=Marilyne |last=Jeunesse |date=2 October 2018 |access-date=22 July 2019 |magazine=[[Teen Vogue]] |language=es |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n=== Film la casa de papel R\u00edo  ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Nothing in Return]]''\n|Dar\u00edo\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''Nomeolvides''\n|Director Assistant\n|Short film\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[1898, Our Last Men in the Philippines]]''\n|Soldado Carvajal\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[The Invisible Guardian]]''\n|Miguel \u00c1ngel\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Some Time Later''\n|Ray\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Alegr\u00eda, tristeza''\n|Terrorist\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''Hasta el cielo''\n|\u00c1ngel\n|\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n|-\n|2017\u2013present\n|''[[Money Heist]]'' \u2018\u2019[[Casa de Papel]]\u2019\u2019\n|An\u00edbal \"R\u00edo\" Cort\u00e9s\n|Main role\n|-\n|2018\u20132019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B3pvfV1JlNN/|title=La 3 temporada de \u00c9lite no contar\u00e1 con la participaci\u00f3n de Miguel Herr\u00e1n (Christian).|publisher=Instagram|date=October 16, 2019|accessdate=October 22, 2019}}</ref>\n|[[\u00c9lite (TV series)|''Elite'']]\n|Christian Varela Exp\u00f3sito\n|Main role (season 1)<br>Guest appearance (season 2) \n(9 episodes)\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Award\n!Category\n!Work\n!Result\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n|[[30th Goya Awards|2016]]\n|[[Goya Awards]]\n|[[Goya Award for Best New Actor|Best New Actor]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |''[[Nothing in Return]]''\n|{{won}}\n|<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.elespanol.com/cultura/20160209/100990267_0.html |title=El Goya que salv\u00f3 mi vida |first=Javier |last=Zurro |date=10 February 2016 |access-date=30 March 2019 |newspaper=[[El Espa\u00f1ol]] |language=es}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|[[C\u00edrculo de Escritores Cinematogr\u00e1ficos|Premios CEC]]\n|Best New Actor\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000179/2016/1/|title=Cinema Writers Circle Awards, Spain (2016)|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n|-\n|2016\n|ASECAN Awards\n|Best Male Performance\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0004228/2016/1/|title=ASECAN (2016)|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-03-30}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=5969653|name=Miguel Herr\u00e1n}}\n\n{{Goya Award Best New Actor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Herr\u00e1n, Miguel}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from M\u00e1laga]]\n[[Category:Spanish male film actors]]\n[[Category:Spanish male television actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Miguel Herr\u00e1n\n| image              = Miguel Herr\u00e1n.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Migu\u00e9l Herr\u00e0n\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1996|04|25}}\n| birth_place        = [[M\u00e1laga]], [[Andalusia]], Spain\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = Spanish\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Actor\n| years_active       = 2015\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Miguel Herr\u00e1n''' (born 25 April 1996) is a Spanish actor. He is best known for playing the roles of An\u00edbal \"R\u00edo\" Cort\u00e9s in ''[[Money Heist]]'' and Christian Varela Exp\u00f3sito in ''[[\u00c9lite (TV series)|\u00c9lite]]''. In 2016, he won the [[Goya Award for Best New Actor]] for his role in the film ''[[Nothing in Return]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nHerr\u00e1n was born in [[M\u00e1laga]] and moved to [[Madrid]] with his mother as a child, where they lived in the [[Chamber\u00ed]] neighborhood. He was not very fond of school and dreamed of growing up to be a car mechanic.\n\n== Career ==\nA chance encounter with actor and director Daniel Guzman in the streets of Malaga led to Herr\u00e1n auditioning for the role of Dario in the film ''[[A cambio de nada]]'', which he won a Goya award for in 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.revistavanityfair.es/sociedad/celebrities/articulos/miguel-herran-jaime-lorente-rio-denver-casa-de-papel-serie-netflix-asi-son-actores-motos-futbol-atletico-madrid-murcia-malaga-instagram-fans/32356 |title=As\u00ed son Miguel Herr\u00e1n y Jaime Lorente, 'hermanos' dentro y fuera de la pantalla |first=Nuria |last=Hern\u00e1ndez |date=17 July 2018 |access-date=22 July 2019 |work=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |language=es |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329210324/https://www.revistavanityfair.es/sociedad/celebrities/articulos/miguel-herran-jaime-lorente-rio-denver-casa-de-papel-serie-netflix-asi-son-actores-motos-futbol-atletico-madrid-murcia-malaga-instagram-fans/32356 |archive-date=29 March 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he was cast as Rio in the Antena 3 series ''[[La casa de papel]]'', which was later picked up by Netflix.