kground:#afeeee;\"|[[1947 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | '''0 / 12'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[US Open (tennis)|US Championships]]\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[1933 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" |A\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | '''0 / 1'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | SR\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 2\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |1 / 3\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |1 / 2\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 2\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 2\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 2\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 0\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" |0 / 1\n| align=\"center\" style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | '''2 / 19'''\n|}\n\nR = tournament restricted to French nationals and held under [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|German occupation]].\n\n<sup>1</sup>In 1946 and 1947, the French Championships were held after Wimbledon.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Tennis performance timeline comparison (women)|Performance timelines for all female tennis players who reached at least one Grand Slam final]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portraitLarge/mw69124/Peggy-Scriven?LinkID=mp64694&role=sit&rNo=0 National Portrait Gallery image]\n\n{{French Open women's singles champions}}\n{{French Open women's doubles champions}}\n{{French Open mixed doubles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Scriven, Margaret}}\n[[Category:English female tennis players]]\n[[Category:French Championships (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Leeds]]\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2001 deaths]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:International Tennis Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:British female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from West Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British tennis player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                              = Margaret Scriven\n|fullname                          = Margaret Croft Scriven-Vivian\n|image                             = Peggy Scriven 1938.jpg\n|image_size                        =\n|caption                           =\n|country                           = {{GBR}}\n|birth_date                        = {{birth date|df=yes|1912|8|12}}\n|birth_place                       = [[Leeds]], England\n|death_date                        = {{death date and age|df=yes|2001|1|25|1912|8|12}}\n|death_place                       = [[Haslemere]], England\n|height                            =\n|turnedpro                         =\n|retired                           =\n|plays                             = Left-handed\n|careerprizemoney                  =\n|tennishofyear                     = 2016\n|tennishofid                       = margaret-peggy-scriven\n|website                           =\n|singlesrecord                     =\n|singlestitles                     =\n|highestsinglesranking             = No. 5 (1933<small>, [[A. Wallis Myers]]</small>)<ref name=\"BudCollins\">{{cite book |author=Collins, Bud |title=The Bud Collins History of Tennis: An Authoritative Encyclopedia and Record Book |publisher=New Chapter Press |location=New York, N.Y |year=2008 |pages=695, 702 |isbn=0-942257-41-3 |oclc= |doi= }}</ref>\n|AustralianOpenresult              =\n|FrenchOpenresult                  = '''W''' ([[1933 French Championships (tennis)|1933]], [[1934 French Championships (tennis)|1934]])\n|Wimbledonresult                   = QF ([[1931 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1931]], [[1933 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1933]], [[1934 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1934]], [[1937 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1937]])\n|USOpenresult                      =\n|Othertournaments                  =\n|doublesrecord                     =\n|doublestitles                     =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult       =\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult           = '''W'''  ([[1935 French Championships (tennis)|1935]])\n|WimbledonDoublesresult            = SF ( [[1934 Wimbledon Championships|1934]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult               = QF (1933)\n|Mixed                             =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult         =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult             = '''W'''  ([[1933 French Championships (tennis)|1933]])\n|WimbledonMixedresult              = QF ([[1937 Wimbledon Championships|1937]])\n|USOpenMixedresult                 = SF (1933)\n}}\n'''Margaret Croft \"Peggy\" Scriven-Vivian''' (''n\u00e9e'' '''Scriven'''; 17 August 1912 \u2013 25 January 2001) was a British [[tennis]] player and the first woman from that country to win the singles title at the [[French Open|French Championships]] in 1933. She also won the singles title at the 1934 French Championships, defeating [[Helen Jacobs]] in the final. She was ranked No. 5 in the world in 1933 and 1934.\n\n==Early Life==\nMargaret Scriven was born on 18 August 1912 at [[Chapel Allerton]], Leeds.<ref name= \"telegraph obit\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1322210/Peggie-Scriven.html|title=Peggie Scriven|last=|first=|date=2001-02-12|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-06-10|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> She was educated at home.<ref name=\"Derby Daily Telegraph 6 June 1933\">{{cite news |title=Peggy Scriven's Triumph |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000520/19330606/059/0007 |accessdate=10 June 2019 |work=Derby Daily Telegraph |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=6 June 1933|page=7|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Her parents were club level tennis players and she played the game from an early age, playing on holiday and entering local tournaments.<ref name=\"The Times (London, England), 2 February 2001\">{{cite news |title=Peggie Scriven |url=http://tinyurl.galegroup.com/tinyurl/AEABU5 |accessdate=11 June 2019 |work=The Times |agency=The Times Digital Archive |date=2 February 2001}}</ref> According to one source, there was a tennis court at her family home and she was coached by her father, Edgar Scriven and by her mother.<ref name=\"Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer 30 June 1931\">{{cite news |title=Miss Scriven of Leeds |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000687/19310630/111/0006 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Yorkshire Post and Leeds Intelligencer |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=30 June 1931|page=6|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nScriven won the British Junior Championships held at Wimbledon in September 1929.<ref name=ayres1937>{{cite book|editor1-last=Myers|editor1-first=A. Wallis|editorlink=A. Wallis Myers|title=Ayres' Lawn Tennis Almanack|year=1937|page=679 |publisher=F.H. Ayres Ltd.|location=London}}</ref> In the final, Scriven defeated Miss P. Burt from Nottingham, 6\u20131, 6\u20133.<ref name=\"Dundee Courier\">{{cite news |title=British Junior Championships |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000564/19290916/037/0003 |accessdate=12 June 2019 |work=Dundee Courier |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=16 September 1929|page=3|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1930, Scriven played at the Wimbledon Championships for the first time, where she was beaten in the first round by Miss K. le Messurier.<ref name=\"Sheffield Daily Telegraph 25 June 1930\">{{cite news |title=Ladies' singles |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000250/19300625/250/0008 |accessdate=12 June 2019 |work=Sheffield Daily Telegraph |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=25 June 1930|page=8|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAt Wimbledon in 1931, Scriven, was far more successful than at first attempt in the previous year. She reached the quarter-finals where she was beaten by the French player, [[Simonne Mathieu]], 1\u20136, 6\u20132, 7\u20135.<ref name=\"Aberdeen Press and Journal 1 July 1931\">{{cite news |title=Thrilling duel at Wimbledon |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000577/19310701/016/0004 |accessdate=12 June 2019 |work=Aberdeen Press and Journal |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=1 July 1931|page=4|url-access=subscription}}</ref>  \n\nIn 1932 she won the singles title at the [[British Covered Court Championships]], played on the wooden courts at the [[Queen's Club]], after a victory in the final against [[Kay Stammers]].<ref name=ayres1937/>\n\nFor the 1933 French Championships, Scriven was not selected to go with the official British touring party. Instead, she travelled to Paris independently.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article247164036|title=PEGGY SCRIVEN, SPARKLING PERSONALITY OF TENNIS|last=|first=|date=1933-11-07|work=Daily Telegraph|access-date=2019-06-12|agency=National Library of Australia|pages=5}}</ref> After beating top British players [[Mary Heeley]] and [[Betty Nuthall]] on her way to the final,<ref name=\"Gloucester Citizen 6 June 1933\">{{cite news |title=\"Peggy\" Scrivens' triumph |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000325/19330606/077/0009 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Gloucester Citizen |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=6 June 1933|page=9|url-access=subscription}}</ref>  Scriven won the tournament, beating Simonne Mathieu in the final. She also triumphed in the mixed doubles, partnered by the Australian player, Jack Crawford.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article94218214|title=IRRESISTIBLE|last=|first=|date=1933-06-02|work=Northern Star|access-date=2019-06-12|agency=National Library of Australia|pages=7}}</ref> \n\nIn early August, 1933, Scriven was part of the losing British team in the [[Wightman Cup]] held at [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills]], New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1933-08-06/ed-1/seq-23/|title=Jacobs saves day as British rally|last=|first=|date=1933-08-06|work=Evening Star|access-date=2019-06-17|via=Library of Congress|pages=3|issn=2331-9968}}</ref>\n\nLater in the same month, Scriven was at Forest Hills for the US Championships. In the singles, she reached the last 16 of the tournament, being knocked out by the American, Josephine Cruickshank.<ref name=\"US championships 1933\">{{Cite news|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1933-08-18/ed-1/seq-18/|title=Only eight remain in US title play|last=|first=|date=1933-08-18|work=Evening Star|access-date=2019-06-17|via=Library of Congress|pages=B\u20134|issn=2331-9968}}</ref> She also competed in the doubles and mixed doubles at the championships. Partnered by the Australian player [[Jack Crawford (tennis)|Jack Crawford]], Scriven reached the semi-finals of the mixed doubles.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1933-08-27/ed-1/seq-50/|title=Invading teams advance|last=|first=|date=1933-08-27|work=Evening Star|access-date=2019-06-17|via=Library of Congress|pages=2|issn=2331-9968}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1934, Scriven was back at the French Championships, this time as part of the official British team.<ref name=\"Western Morning News 1 June 1934\">{{cite news |title=A British victory |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000329/19340601/079/0007 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Western Morning News |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=1 June 1934|page=7|url-access=subscription}}</ref> On 3 June 1934, Scriven retained her French title, beating Helen Jacobs of America, 7\u20135, 4\u20136, 6\u20131.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1934-06-03/ed-1/seq-59/|title=Bow in surprises in French events|last=|first=|date=1934-06-03|work=Evening Star|access-date=2019-06-12|agency=Library of Congress|page=59|issn=2331-9968}}</ref> The final started at the late time of 6.30pm and, after two sets had been played, both players appealed against the light. The appeal was turned down, however, and the match continued in twilight. After 3 more games, with Scriven leading 2\u20131, Jacobs appealed again against the light but was turned down. Scriven went on to win all the remaining games.<ref name=\"Daily Herald 4 June 1934\">{{cite news |title=Favourite for Wimbledon |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000681/19340604/380/0018 |accessdate=26 June 2019 |work=Daily Herald |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=4 June 1934|page=18|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nAt the French Championships in 1935, Scriven was unable to win the singles for the third time, being beaten in the semi-finals. However, she did win the doubles, partnered by Katherine Stammers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83045462/1935-05-27/ed-1/seq-15/|title=Yankees survive in French tennis|last=|first=|date=1935-05-27|work=Evening Star|access-date=2019-06-13|via=Library of Congress|pages=A\u201315|issn=2331-9968}}</ref>\n\nScriven-Vivian was the last British woman to win the same [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] singles tournament for two consecutive years. In addition, she was the first left-handed woman to win a Grand Slam singles title and was the only unseeded woman ever to win the French Championships or [[French Open]] until the [[2017 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2017 singles title]] was won by [[Je\u013cena Ostapenko]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Steven|title=French Open fairytales|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/blogs/sport/story/307925.html|publisher=[[ESPN UK]]|website=espn.co.uk|date=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/tennis/40233490|title= French Open: Jelena Ostapenko beats Simona Halep to win first Grand Slam|date=10 June 2017|work=[[BBC Sport]]}}</ref>\t\t\n\nShe played for the British [[Wightman Cup]] team in 1933, 1934 and 1938.\n\nAccording to [[A. Wallis Myers]] of [[Daily Telegraph|The Daily Telegraph]] and the [[Daily Mail]], Scriven-Vivian was ranked in the world top ten from 1933 through 1935, reaching a career high of World No. 5 in those rankings in 1933 and 1934.<ref name=\"BudCollins\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nScriven married Harvey Vivian on 28 November 1940<ref name=\"Gloucestershire Echo 29 November 1940\">{{cite news |title=Peggy Scriven |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000320/19401129/077/0006 |accessdate=10 June 2019 |work=Gloucestershire Echo |via=The British Newspaper Archive |date=29 November 1940|page=6|url-access=subscription}}</ref> who was a house master and a wartime RAF officer. The couple had a son and a daughter.<ref name= \"telegraph obit\"/>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n===Singles (2 titles)===\n{| class='sortable wikitable' \n!style=\"width:65px\"|'''Outcome'''\n!style=\"width:30px\"|'''Year'''\n!style=\"width:200px\"|'''Championship'''\n!style=\"width:50px\"|'''Surface'''\n!style=\"width:200px\"|'''Opponent'''\n!style=\"width:150px\" c